  "text": "BNP and troponin Our search retrieved three papers that examined the predictive value of both BNP and troponins. Two of these three looked at the predictive power of combining the two biomarkers. A prospective cohort study found that while elevations each of NT-proBNP and troponin T measured at admission were associated with a statistically significant increase in 30-day mortality ( p<0.001), an elevation of either NT-proBNP or troponin was associated with a 15-fold increased risk of mortality compared with patients with normal levels of both biomarkers. [CITATION_1] The risk of mortality was 30-fold greater than in patients with normal levels of both biomarkers. [CITATION_2] A prospective observational study looked at the association of elevated NT-proBNP and troponin T at admission and discharge with mortality, repeat hospitalisation and a composite outcome of both repeat hospitalisation and death as outcomes. [CITATION_3] It was found that only recurrent hospitalisations were associated with elevated troponin T and NT-proBNP at discharge ( p=0.013). Elevated troponin T and NT-proBNP at admission were not significantly associated with any outcome.",
